1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
https://slama.dev/comeback/

2
00:00:08,850 --> 00:00:10,420
It's five o'clock, where's Ozzak?

3
00:00:10,750 --> 00:00:13,450
He said he won't be attending any Christmas meeting.

4
00:00:13,640 --> 00:00:15,420
But we're only doing it because of him.

5
00:00:15,640 --> 00:00:17,100
I don't know, just call him somehow.

6
00:00:20,650 --> 00:00:22,350
Ozzak, there's beer on the table!

7
00:00:27,740 --> 00:00:29,320
I always fall for that.

8
00:00:59,750 --> 00:01:04,820
I got a Christmas tree, so Ozzak, you won't be going to the forest this year.

9
00:01:04,820 --> 00:01:06,200
Ugh, here we go again.

10
00:01:06,200 --> 00:01:09,150
I think last year there was unnecessary fuss about it.

11
00:01:09,250 --> 00:01:12,750
Bro, Frantisek Palacky died under that tree.

12
00:01:14,250 --> 00:01:17,050
She brought it with the memorial plaque and all.

13
00:01:18,250 --> 00:01:19,250
And it was an oak.

14
00:01:21,150 --> 00:01:23,150
This year we'll have this one.

15
00:01:23,550 --> 00:01:27,430
I got it as a bonus for selling a thousand hamster Mirecek toys.

16
00:01:27,950 --> 00:01:31,450
It's true that too many trees get cut down for Christmas.

17
00:01:32,350 --> 00:01:33,950
So one more won't be missed.

18
00:01:34,550 --> 00:01:36,050
Last year's fir tree is still under the bathtub.

19
00:01:37,050 --> 00:01:40,190
Can't we just have one Christmas that we'll all fondly remember?

20
00:01:40,450 --> 00:01:43,190
Yeah, last year's is also remembered by the city police.

21
00:01:43,190 --> 00:01:44,290
Some ambulances?

22
00:01:45,350 --> 00:01:47,350
Carp is traditional Christmas food.

23
00:01:47,550 --> 00:01:49,780
But each of us has already swallowed a bone once.

24
00:01:49,780 --> 00:01:51,020
Ozzak even twice.

25
00:01:51,100 --> 00:01:51,780
The same one.

26
00:01:52,240 --> 00:01:53,280
I wanted seconds.

27
00:01:56,400 --> 00:01:57,700
I'm warning you.

28
00:01:57,700 --> 00:02:02,550
Take note that this year, Christmas at our place will be a holiday of peace.

29
00:02:07,450 --> 00:02:08,110
Where's the bathtub?

30
00:02:29,150 --> 00:02:32,160
That hamster Mirecek is driving me crazy, listening to it here all day.

31
00:02:32,160 --> 00:02:33,420
Oh gosh, sorry Tomas.

32
00:02:33,560 --> 00:02:36,120
That hamster Mirecek is driving me crazy, listening to it here all day.

33
00:02:36,620 --> 00:02:38,420
And people are buying it like crazy, huh?

34
00:02:38,580 --> 00:02:39,600
Yeah, kids love it.

35
00:02:39,740 --> 00:02:40,560
The sales will be great.

36
00:02:41,270 --> 00:02:42,710
Looks like there'll be a pre-Christmas bonus.

37
00:02:42,710 --> 00:02:47,950
Well, don't expect anything big, but you'll be able to buy some little thing for Zoran as a Christmas present.

38
00:02:48,230 --> 00:02:50,150
I'd never buy it for myself, but...

39
00:02:50,150 --> 00:02:51,850
Kids love it, these things.

40
00:02:53,250 --> 00:02:53,790
Bye.

41
00:02:53,790 --> 00:02:54,310
Bye.

42
00:02:56,250 --> 00:02:58,350
Zoran and I don't celebrate Christmas.

43
00:02:59,050 --> 00:03:00,050
You don't?

44
00:03:02,050 --> 00:03:06,820
Zoran and I think that at Christmas, people should be together and not running around shopping malls.

45
00:03:06,820 --> 00:03:08,280
So we're flying to Barbados.

46
00:03:10,650 --> 00:03:14,650
Zoran has business meetings there and I'll enjoy some peace and quiet.

47
00:03:15,200 --> 00:03:15,720
Not at all.

48
00:03:15,720 --> 00:03:17,350
I don't envy you those nerves.

49
00:03:22,250 --> 00:03:24,130
I won't have any stress this year.

50
00:03:24,350 --> 00:03:26,370
This year Lexa here is buying presents for me.

51
00:03:26,750 --> 00:03:27,750
Online.

52
00:03:33,050 --> 00:03:35,450
Does that seem like a good idea to you?

53
00:03:36,550 --> 00:03:37,950
I'll owe him for it.

54
00:03:42,180 --> 00:03:43,080
Hey, Lexa.

55
00:03:43,080 --> 00:03:46,240
I was just telling Marcelka how great our gift plan is.

56
00:03:46,240 --> 00:03:46,640
This year.

57
00:03:46,940 --> 00:03:48,140
It's all ordered already.

58
00:03:48,650 --> 00:03:50,350
Did they have everything from the list?

59
00:03:50,630 --> 00:03:51,790
What list?

60
00:03:54,690 --> 00:03:55,630
That was real.

61
00:03:55,630 --> 00:04:00,350
I have the paper, but I'll tell you, your handwriting is seriously hardcore.

62
00:04:01,110 --> 00:04:01,670
Excuse me.

63
00:04:02,320 --> 00:04:03,840
I happen to have neat handwriting.

64
00:04:04,280 --> 00:04:05,720
Neat, but illegible.

65
00:04:06,150 --> 00:04:09,850
Last time you ordered Leona Machalkova, they delivered Glenn Miller.

66
00:04:10,650 --> 00:04:12,350
But I did figure it out in the end.

67
00:04:12,650 --> 00:04:14,750
I just don't get who you wanted to give the opossum to.

68
00:04:16,950 --> 00:04:18,650
Opossum?

69
00:04:19,580 --> 00:04:20,460
They didn't have the same one.

70
00:04:22,690 --> 00:04:24,870
Mr. Pacovsky, could I ask you for something too?

71
00:04:25,130 --> 00:04:25,650
Of course.

72
00:04:25,810 --> 00:04:28,110
Can I come watch TV at your place on Christmas Eve?

73
00:04:28,410 --> 00:04:29,170
You don't have one?

74
00:04:30,050 --> 00:04:31,190
They cut off our electricity.

75
00:04:31,550 --> 00:04:34,650
But mom said we can't tell anyone so people don't come feel sorry for us.

76
00:04:35,790 --> 00:04:36,310
Poor thing.

77
00:04:37,510 --> 00:04:38,030
Alright.

78
00:04:39,650 --> 00:04:42,330
And Three Wishes for Cinderella, that's something we can watch together.

79
00:04:42,330 --> 00:04:43,270
Yeah, that too.

80
00:04:43,270 --> 00:04:46,230
But mainly the Miss Wet T-Shirt finale from Barbados.

81
00:04:46,230 --> 00:04:46,690
What?

82
00:04:47,550 --> 00:04:49,350
Why does it always have to be on Christmas Eve?

83
00:04:50,110 --> 00:04:51,130
Ozzak said.

84
00:04:51,970 --> 00:04:53,630
They moved it because of hurricane Dalibor.

85
00:04:54,060 --> 00:04:54,760
Oh right.

86
00:04:56,150 --> 00:04:57,950
I hope not to the Paradise hotel.

87
00:04:58,150 --> 00:05:02,560
I was looking forward to some peace and quiet there, and instead there'd be half-naked women running around.

88
00:05:02,560 --> 00:05:04,680
And Zoran needs peace for his business meetings.

89
00:05:09,450 --> 00:05:10,850
He's just texting me now.

90
00:05:11,350 --> 00:05:15,820
Dear Marcela, I need peace for business meetings, so I'll go alone.

91
00:05:15,820 --> 00:05:16,680
Feed the fish.

92
00:05:17,950 --> 00:05:18,550
Zoran.

93
00:05:20,550 --> 00:05:22,950
Wow, he's really to be pitied.

94
00:05:23,250 --> 00:05:27,750
Alone in a hotel full of busty women and he'll be having business meetings.

95
00:05:49,350 --> 00:05:53,050
Two kilos of yeast, rum, half a kilo of caraway, ten kilos of flour.

96
00:05:53,750 --> 00:05:54,330
Coarse.

97
00:05:54,430 --> 00:05:55,770
That's flour for a real man.

98
00:05:55,770 --> 00:05:57,790
I want beer rolls.

99
00:05:57,950 --> 00:05:58,650
So you say.

100
00:05:59,420 --> 00:06:01,620
Last year I had one and danced at midnight mass.

101
00:06:01,620 --> 00:06:02,740
This year I really can't handle it.

102
00:06:03,000 --> 00:06:04,060
Christmas cookies, the way they should be.

103
00:06:04,520 --> 00:06:05,340
Ivuska, look.

104
00:06:06,050 --> 00:06:07,350
Pardubice twenty-sixer.

105
00:06:11,150 --> 00:06:12,350
Not for the faint of heart.

106
00:06:12,850 --> 00:06:14,350
The EU banned it.

107
00:06:14,380 --> 00:06:16,020
But they can't get us.

108
00:06:17,550 --> 00:06:19,780
And if you want one tray, I'll start with a tenner.

109
00:06:19,780 --> 00:06:20,380
For you.

110
00:06:20,900 --> 00:06:22,000
But it won't be the same.

111
00:06:22,200 --> 00:06:22,960
No, thanks.

112
00:06:22,980 --> 00:06:24,460
I'll stick with Linzer cookies.

113
00:06:25,870 --> 00:06:26,590
Wow.

114
00:06:27,350 --> 00:06:28,750
There'll be rum balls too, right?

115
00:06:29,050 --> 00:06:30,250
I'll be filling them in a minute.

116
00:06:30,460 --> 00:06:31,780
But only half doses.

117
00:06:32,100 --> 00:06:34,540
I don't want them exploding in the oven again.

118
00:06:34,720 --> 00:06:35,520
Exactly.

119
00:06:39,670 --> 00:06:41,030
I'm ready, Mr. Ozzak.

120
00:06:41,570 --> 00:06:43,010
Lexa, you call that ready?

121
00:06:43,610 --> 00:06:44,790
Where are your safety goggles?

122
00:06:45,980 --> 00:06:46,420
Here.

123
00:06:47,650 --> 00:06:48,250
Ivo, hey.

124
00:06:49,650 --> 00:06:50,350
Ivo, I know what you're getting for Christmas.

125
00:06:52,050 --> 00:06:54,270
Well unfortunately so do I, dad always gives me the same thing.

126
00:06:54,830 --> 00:06:55,870
So should I not tell you?

127
00:06:56,450 --> 00:07:00,850
Don't you dare, at least this way I have some hope.

128
00:07:07,070 --> 00:07:08,650
Are you looking forward to Christmas, Mr. Ozzak?

129
00:07:08,990 --> 00:07:10,010
Who wouldn't be?

130
00:07:11,050 --> 00:07:12,820
I just hate how soft they've gotten.

131
00:07:13,250 --> 00:07:15,150
In the old days it had more edge.

132
00:07:15,650 --> 00:07:16,750
What old days?

133
00:07:17,030 --> 00:07:19,450
When men were men and perfume was a dirty word.

134
00:07:19,970 --> 00:07:21,510
Nowadays it's a holiday for softies.

135
00:07:22,650 --> 00:07:23,940
Should I put the baking powder in?

136
00:07:24,050 --> 00:07:25,500
Powder, that's it, powder.

137
00:07:25,750 --> 00:07:27,750
All diminutives, all soft words.

138
00:07:28,050 --> 00:07:32,850
Powder, little tree, little balls, little rolls, fairy tales, vanilla.

139
00:07:32,850 --> 00:07:38,220
Yeah, back in the day you just chopped down a tree, made balls and rolls.

140
00:07:38,220 --> 00:07:39,760
And then everyone stuffed their faces.

141
00:07:40,570 --> 00:07:42,050
Yeah, those were the days, Lexa.

142
00:07:43,650 --> 00:07:46,380
Should I put the powder in the baking thing.

143
00:07:46,650 --> 00:07:47,850
Throw it in, boy.

144
00:07:50,450 --> 00:07:51,010
Alright.

145
00:07:52,450 --> 00:07:54,150
And you can stir.

146
00:07:57,470 --> 00:07:59,570
But carp, that's a pretty tough word, right?

147
00:07:59,630 --> 00:08:00,770
But a soft fish.

148
00:08:00,970 --> 00:08:01,790
It doesn't even have teeth.

149
00:08:02,290 --> 00:08:04,650
Yeah, a swordfish, that's different.

150
00:08:04,750 --> 00:08:05,710
Or a stingray.

151
00:08:05,950 --> 00:08:06,510
Electric.

152
00:08:06,750 --> 00:08:07,310
Right.

153
00:08:07,310 --> 00:08:08,970
Or a shark.

154
00:08:08,970 --> 00:08:10,770
Any old lady can kill a carp.

155
00:08:10,930 --> 00:08:13,010
But try going after a shark with a mallet.

156
00:08:14,250 --> 00:08:15,050
A mallet?

157
00:08:15,050 --> 00:08:17,090
A club.

158
00:08:18,750 --> 00:08:20,750
That would be truly manly.

159
00:08:21,350 --> 00:08:21,950
Enough.

160
00:08:23,950 --> 00:08:26,650
Right, now we let it rise.

161
00:08:27,150 --> 00:08:28,450
But we need to watch it.

162
00:08:29,050 --> 00:08:31,250
As soon as it moves, we have five minutes.

163
00:08:31,650 --> 00:08:32,550
Are we going to shape it?

164
00:08:33,150 --> 00:08:33,950
Or run.

165
00:08:35,550 --> 00:08:36,550
Now let's do the balls.

166
00:08:36,950 --> 00:08:37,850
With vanilla.

167
00:08:38,280 --> 00:08:38,800
Sure.

168
00:09:00,310 --> 00:09:00,830
Sorry.

169
00:09:01,550 --> 00:09:04,930
That hamster Mirecek is driving me crazy, listening to it here all day.

170
00:09:04,950 --> 00:09:06,150
What Mirecek?

171
00:09:06,550 --> 00:09:08,070
Well, kids love it.

172
00:09:08,250 --> 00:09:10,830
Hey, my stove broke down at home somehow.

173
00:09:10,830 --> 00:09:12,070
Oh, I'm sorry to hear that.

174
00:09:12,290 --> 00:09:14,230
Nobody needs to feel sorry for us, we're doing fine.

175
00:09:16,050 --> 00:09:17,350
Sorry, it's the Christmas season.

176
00:09:17,650 --> 00:09:19,150
Everyone just feels sorry for everyone.

177
00:09:19,950 --> 00:09:22,550
I'd need to make Christmas Eve dinner for the kids.

178
00:09:23,050 --> 00:09:26,830
Well, I don't know, Iva always gets nervous in the kitchen, so don't get in the way.

179
00:09:26,830 --> 00:09:29,010
And I won't be in the way, fries take seven minutes.

180
00:09:29,890 --> 00:09:31,070
You're making fries?

181
00:09:32,250 --> 00:09:35,210
Of course, it's Christmas Eve, so the kids should have something proper.

182
00:09:35,210 --> 00:09:35,650
I see.

183
00:09:36,350 --> 00:09:37,450
And do you have presents?

184
00:09:37,650 --> 00:09:39,210
No, I didn't have time for those again.

185
00:09:39,430 --> 00:09:40,950
I'll buy them before the fries are done.

186
00:09:41,190 --> 00:09:41,810
Online?

187
00:09:42,270 --> 00:09:43,530
At the gas station.

188
00:09:45,450 --> 00:09:46,450
Sure.

189
00:09:51,750 --> 00:09:58,750
These are Christmas 2004, 2005, 2006, and 2007.

190
00:10:01,650 --> 00:10:02,870
This one's actually good.

191
00:10:02,870 --> 00:10:03,570
You think?

192
00:10:04,850 --> 00:10:11,230
I don't want another jacket from the Vietnamese market.

193
00:10:11,850 --> 00:10:13,030
I wouldn't mind a jacket.

194
00:10:13,350 --> 00:10:16,670
I got a scented tree air freshener from him and Lexa got a windshield wiper.

195
00:10:16,670 --> 00:10:17,170
Just one?

196
00:10:17,410 --> 00:10:18,830
He doesn't even have a license.

197
00:10:21,440 --> 00:10:22,120
Hi.

198
00:10:23,450 --> 00:10:27,150
Hey, that's the jacket you wear to the dumpsters.

199
00:10:28,150 --> 00:10:29,150
It's really nice.

200
00:10:29,550 --> 00:10:33,350
How am I supposed to look forward to Christmas when dad picks the gifts and Lexa orders them.

201
00:10:40,850 --> 00:10:41,850
The hamster's sold out.

202
00:10:41,850 --> 00:10:42,530
Too bad.

203
00:10:43,920 --> 00:10:44,600
What?

204
00:10:45,550 --> 00:10:46,650
I wanted seconds.

205
00:10:49,580 --> 00:10:50,640
That was chicken.

206
00:10:51,690 --> 00:10:52,370
Oh.

207
00:10:54,550 --> 00:10:55,550
Hamster, Mirecek, those carols.

208
00:10:57,550 --> 00:11:00,950
Well, like they said, as long as you keep playing them, they won't come back to the shop.

209
00:11:01,590 --> 00:11:02,070
Oh.

210
00:11:02,850 --> 00:11:04,250
Well, they're sold out.

211
00:11:04,750 --> 00:11:07,250
So you can go back to the shop.

212
00:11:07,390 --> 00:11:07,870
Too bad.

213
00:11:08,870 --> 00:11:09,350
Yeah.

214
00:11:13,250 --> 00:11:14,850
It's getting cold, huh?

215
00:11:15,670 --> 00:11:16,150
Father!

216
00:11:17,950 --> 00:11:19,550
What? I just said it's getting cold.

217
00:11:19,950 --> 00:11:21,850
I know exactly why you're saying that.

218
00:11:21,850 --> 00:11:23,330
You only have one kidney.

219
00:11:23,970 --> 00:11:26,070
I hate practical gifts.

220
00:11:26,650 --> 00:11:29,950
You just touch it, feel it's soft, and you lose all desire to unwrap it.

221
00:11:29,950 --> 00:11:30,790
Soft gifts.

222
00:11:31,090 --> 00:11:31,570
Right.

223
00:11:32,350 --> 00:11:34,090
Soft words and soft gifts.

224
00:11:34,090 --> 00:11:35,510
That's the worst thing about Christmas.

225
00:11:35,630 --> 00:11:37,410
I've never given you a soft gift.

226
00:11:37,570 --> 00:11:38,710
Once I got wine.

227
00:11:39,840 --> 00:11:42,580
And Ivuska, I haven't always given you soft gifts either.

228
00:11:43,120 --> 00:11:44,300
The last hard one was when I was seven.

229
00:11:44,440 --> 00:11:44,920
A vacuum cleaner.

230
00:11:45,100 --> 00:11:48,280
You told me it was a little elephant helper and since then I've had to vacuum.

231
00:11:48,820 --> 00:11:51,000
But then I never gave you another vacuum cleaner.

232
00:11:51,480 --> 00:11:54,060
No, but an iron, a drying rack, and a stepladder.

233
00:11:54,120 --> 00:11:56,180
And then came the long era of winter jackets.

234
00:11:57,750 --> 00:11:59,350
Weren't you happy with them?

235
00:11:59,850 --> 00:12:00,750
Happy?

236
00:12:00,850 --> 00:12:02,690
Yeah, maybe a little with the first one.

237
00:12:02,850 --> 00:12:04,850
But every girl wants something to wear.

238
00:12:05,450 --> 00:12:07,690
But every girl wants to pick it out herself.

239
00:12:07,690 --> 00:12:09,230
But then it's not a surprise.

240
00:12:09,370 --> 00:12:11,470
And a gift should be a surprise.

241
00:12:11,650 --> 00:12:13,150
I hope I'll be surprised this year.

242
00:12:16,650 --> 00:12:19,850
So I'm not getting the beer encyclopedia this year?

243
00:12:23,030 --> 00:12:23,590
Great.

244
00:12:33,770 --> 00:12:34,330
Bye.

245
00:12:34,550 --> 00:12:34,990
Hi.

246
00:12:36,650 --> 00:12:37,450
What was wrong with it?

247
00:12:38,150 --> 00:12:38,750
With what?

248
00:12:39,350 --> 00:12:40,250
The hamster.

249
00:12:44,150 --> 00:12:44,950
That it died.

250
00:12:46,850 --> 00:12:47,850
Ran out?

251
00:12:48,350 --> 00:12:50,050
That's clearly a D, isn't it?

252
00:12:50,950 --> 00:12:55,650
It looks like a P. And I also more or less guessed the hamster part.

253
00:13:00,350 --> 00:13:02,710
Marcelka, when I said you could take time off?

254
00:13:02,710 --> 00:13:03,910
I'm perfectly calm.

255
00:13:04,650 --> 00:13:07,200
I'm taking an emotional venting course.

256
00:13:07,350 --> 00:13:08,750
Mmm, wind level two, right?

257
00:13:10,320 --> 00:13:11,540
It's a kind of mantra.

258
00:13:12,450 --> 00:13:19,630
I'll take the Christmas shift.

259
00:13:19,750 --> 00:13:21,910
But Marcelka, you don't have to, Ozzak can handle it.

260
00:13:22,150 --> 00:13:25,750
And if they happen to deliver the hamster Mirecek, I've allowed him one rum ball.

261
00:13:26,050 --> 00:13:28,750
No, let him enjoy Christmas too.

262
00:13:36,250 --> 00:13:38,530
Mr. Pacovsky, wouldn't it be better to write "from a dream" there?

263
00:13:38,530 --> 00:13:39,370
Sounds better.

264
00:13:52,550 --> 00:13:54,350
You wanted to speak with me, Mr. Pacovsky?

265
00:13:55,850 --> 00:13:57,150
Have a seat, Lexa.

266
00:14:01,750 --> 00:14:02,230
Yeah?

267
00:14:02,230 --> 00:14:03,610
The presents arrived already?

268
00:14:03,610 --> 00:14:04,090
Great.

269
00:14:07,550 --> 00:14:08,850
The presents arrived, Lexa.

270
00:14:09,230 --> 00:14:11,310
The presents that you ordered.

271
00:14:13,650 --> 00:14:20,950
Can you please show me where on my list there's a steam sauna?

272
00:14:21,630 --> 00:14:22,110
Here.

273
00:14:22,330 --> 00:14:23,330
Right under the opossum.

274
00:14:25,250 --> 00:14:26,250
They really didn't have that one.

275
00:14:30,650 --> 00:14:33,350
Lexa, I don't see steam sauna here.

276
00:14:34,350 --> 00:14:37,750
What I see here is winter jacket.

277
00:14:38,080 --> 00:14:41,510
That was the second option.

278
00:14:41,850 --> 00:14:42,870
Actually the third.

279
00:14:44,950 --> 00:14:45,950
And the second?

280
00:14:46,850 --> 00:14:47,650
Beer probe.

281
00:14:48,250 --> 00:14:49,550
But Mr. Ozzak already has one.

282
00:14:54,550 --> 00:15:01,050
Lexa, please, how can someone confuse a winter jacket with a steam sauna?

283
00:15:03,450 --> 00:15:05,350
They have the same number of letters.

284
00:15:10,750 --> 00:15:12,800
So you'll return the steam sauna.

285
00:15:13,150 --> 00:15:17,850
And tomorrow I want a beautiful winter jacket here.

286
00:15:19,250 --> 00:15:20,610
More like sometime in January.

287
00:15:21,050 --> 00:15:23,010
They have a thirty-day processing period.

288
00:15:26,050 --> 00:15:30,450
Are you telling me that this year I'll have to give someone a steam sauna for Christmas?

289
00:15:30,760 --> 00:15:32,180
That's one option.

290
00:15:34,050 --> 00:15:34,950
The other?

291
00:15:35,950 --> 00:15:36,950
Christmas in January.

292
00:15:46,060 --> 00:15:47,020
Mr. Pacovsky.

293
00:15:47,080 --> 00:15:47,280
Yes?

294
00:15:48,750 --> 00:15:51,550
I wanted to ask, what was the opossum?

295
00:15:56,770 --> 00:15:57,370
Opossum?

296
00:15:58,450 --> 00:15:59,450
Ivuska.

297
00:16:01,150 --> 00:16:01,650
Right.

298
00:16:09,570 --> 00:16:10,130
Open-face sandwich.

299
00:16:10,950 --> 00:16:12,410
Is that food for a man?

300
00:16:12,950 --> 00:16:14,110
That's for dad, uncle.

301
00:16:14,550 --> 00:16:16,330
For you I have a big sandwich.

302
00:16:16,750 --> 00:16:18,250
No way!

303
00:16:19,150 --> 00:16:27,350
Hey, bro, what about that steam sauna you were talking about yesterday?

304
00:16:28,250 --> 00:16:29,150
I was talking about it?

305
00:16:30,450 --> 00:16:31,150
Of course.

306
00:16:31,550 --> 00:16:32,870
You were talking about it all evening.

307
00:16:32,870 --> 00:16:33,290
Wait.

308
00:16:33,850 --> 00:16:36,710
He was at the pub all evening and when he came back, he didn't talk at all.

309
00:16:36,850 --> 00:16:38,090
Well actually I told him that.

310
00:16:38,090 --> 00:16:38,490
Wait.

311
00:16:38,950 --> 00:16:39,750
What did I say?

312
00:16:40,450 --> 00:16:42,250
That you've been wanting one your whole life.

313
00:16:43,090 --> 00:16:44,330
Wasn't it a steam roller?

314
00:16:44,510 --> 00:16:45,230
No, a sauna.

315
00:16:45,950 --> 00:16:49,850
Well I was surprised too, you and a steam sauna don't go together at all.

316
00:16:50,250 --> 00:16:51,350
Well, good.

317
00:16:51,590 --> 00:16:53,130
Uncle, you want a steam sauna?

318
00:16:53,430 --> 00:16:55,650
Sure, I was talking about it all evening yesterday.

319
00:16:56,650 --> 00:17:03,650
Just so you realize, when you start talking about certain things before Christmas, they tend to show up under the tree.

320
00:17:03,850 --> 00:17:05,650
I'm never that lucky.

321
00:17:06,350 --> 00:17:08,420
I'm sure I'll get the beer encyclopedia again.

322
00:17:29,250 --> 00:17:30,650
I need to hang it above that.

323
00:17:31,350 --> 00:17:32,200
That's a star.

324
00:17:37,650 --> 00:17:39,550
And Hendrix as the dark one in the back.

325
00:17:40,550 --> 00:17:41,150
Nonsense.

326
00:17:41,650 --> 00:17:42,950
Hendrix, always in the front.

327
00:17:54,350 --> 00:17:56,050
Hey, is your old man at the beach already?

328
00:17:56,060 --> 00:17:57,320
I don't care.

329
00:17:57,380 --> 00:17:58,200
But I do.

330
00:17:58,750 --> 00:18:01,420
Could you call him to send me a shark?

331
00:18:01,420 --> 00:18:01,900
What?

332
00:18:02,300 --> 00:18:04,690
Or a stingray, or a swordfish.

333
00:18:04,770 --> 00:18:05,570
Something with teeth.

334
00:18:05,710 --> 00:18:06,570
Or with electricity.

335
00:18:08,150 --> 00:18:10,150
I'd like to toughen up Christmas a bit this year.

336
00:18:10,550 --> 00:18:11,850
His phone is off.

337
00:18:13,150 --> 00:18:14,450
Or I got it wet.

338
00:18:15,050 --> 00:18:16,750
Send him a telegram maybe.

339
00:18:17,350 --> 00:18:18,150
Address?

340
00:18:18,300 --> 00:18:19,040
Croatian sleaze...

341
00:18:19,040 --> 00:18:19,520
Hold on, hold on.

342
00:18:21,150 --> 00:18:26,450
Croatian sleazebag, hotel with busty babes, Barbados.

343
00:18:28,250 --> 00:18:29,050
Thanks, mambo.

344
00:18:33,150 --> 00:18:37,450
Mr. Ozzak, Three Wishes for Cinderella is on, don't you want to watch it too?

345
00:18:38,750 --> 00:18:42,450
Well, I still prefer the Melnik Ozzak.

346
00:18:45,850 --> 00:18:50,650
Little bird, where is your nest?

347
00:18:56,450 --> 00:18:59,150
"Where is your nest, bird" would be much better.

348
00:19:00,050 --> 00:19:00,850
My thoughts exactly.

349
00:19:01,410 --> 00:19:01,890
Uncle!

350
00:19:02,650 --> 00:19:05,150
The checkup went well, that delivery boy who delivers newspapers.

351
00:19:05,650 --> 00:19:09,150
A guy at sixteen should already know what a drunk tank looks like from the inside.

352
00:19:11,370 --> 00:19:12,730
Hey, that's nice.

353
00:19:12,730 --> 00:19:14,350
Tomorrow it's Christmas again.

354
00:19:14,350 --> 00:19:15,770
In the morning we'll decorate the ficus.

355
00:19:16,050 --> 00:19:18,630
Yeah, we'll have fries with ketchup.

356
00:19:18,630 --> 00:19:21,250
And I can have extra since it's the holidays.

357
00:19:21,450 --> 00:19:25,420
Don't kid yourself, you always end up coming to our place and eating a whole tray of cookies.

358
00:19:25,420 --> 00:19:26,600
This year we'll have our own.

359
00:19:26,700 --> 00:19:28,520
Mom saves cookies from her coffee all year long.

360
00:19:29,320 --> 00:19:30,940
Caramel cookies are the best.

361
00:19:31,950 --> 00:19:34,050
Almond ones are also the best, but less so.

362
00:19:34,750 --> 00:19:37,220
Then mom remembers that Santa is fueling up around the corner.

363
00:19:37,450 --> 00:19:38,950
And she runs out for presents.

364
00:19:40,150 --> 00:19:41,950
Santa isn't the same one, so we make do.

365
00:19:43,250 --> 00:19:44,550
Then we call dad.

366
00:19:45,050 --> 00:19:46,650
We wish him a merry Christmas.

367
00:19:47,050 --> 00:19:50,890
And mom wishes that his bimbo robs him as soon as possible, like he robbed us.

368
00:19:53,150 --> 00:19:54,350
We sing "Let's Go Together to Bethlehem" and mom starts crying.

369
00:19:54,850 --> 00:19:56,850
Yeah, Christmas.

370
00:19:56,940 --> 00:19:59,720
Hmm, they get me down a little sometimes.

371
00:20:00,220 --> 00:20:00,760
Why?

372
00:20:00,760 --> 00:20:01,520
They're nice.

373
00:20:04,250 --> 00:20:05,050
Travnicek.

374
00:20:05,470 --> 00:20:06,710
Is that a name for a man?

375
00:20:20,330 --> 00:20:20,870
Marcelka?

376
00:20:22,850 --> 00:20:24,050
The fir trees are going, Tomas.

377
00:20:24,250 --> 00:20:26,450
Ozzak is sending you some cookies.

378
00:20:27,950 --> 00:20:29,380
He's saying something about a telegram.

379
00:20:29,380 --> 00:20:30,240
Welcome.

380
00:20:31,450 --> 00:20:32,050
Careful.

381
00:20:33,560 --> 00:20:35,660
You shouldn't drive for two or three hours after eating those.

382
00:20:36,180 --> 00:20:37,540
I'm not going anywhere anyway.

383
00:20:39,350 --> 00:20:40,650
Wind level two, no...

384
00:20:46,250 --> 00:20:46,920
I'm fine.

385
00:20:48,850 --> 00:20:50,350
They only had gas at the station.

386
00:20:50,650 --> 00:20:51,370
What should I do?

387
00:20:51,650 --> 00:20:52,850
Have a roll.

388
00:21:03,300 --> 00:21:03,760
Hey, uncle.

389
00:21:04,950 --> 00:21:05,450
See?

390
00:21:06,450 --> 00:21:07,650
I only cut off the top.

391
00:21:08,450 --> 00:21:09,830
The rest is still standing in Old Town Square.

392
00:21:12,350 --> 00:21:14,450
And one more roll.

393
00:21:17,530 --> 00:21:17,990
Hi.

394
00:21:18,870 --> 00:21:20,530
We can't send her home like this.

395
00:21:20,670 --> 00:21:21,110
Come on.

396
00:21:22,160 --> 00:21:22,620
Bye.

397
00:21:25,210 --> 00:21:25,670
Bye.

398
00:21:26,250 --> 00:21:27,110
Need a deep fryer?

399
00:21:27,110 --> 00:21:28,410
No, these go on a baking sheet.

400
00:21:28,770 --> 00:21:29,590
They're not alone.

401
00:21:30,190 --> 00:21:30,650
Hey.

402
00:21:32,150 --> 00:21:36,450
Ozzak, are you sick that a woman has to drink on your behalf?

403
00:21:36,830 --> 00:21:37,470
Hey, listen.

404
00:21:37,960 --> 00:21:40,420
I was thinking, wouldn't you like to have schnitzel with us?

405
00:21:40,560 --> 00:21:41,620
We're doing fine.

406
00:21:41,660 --> 00:21:44,340
I know, but we have way too many.

407
00:21:45,280 --> 00:21:46,060
Alright.

408
00:21:46,260 --> 00:21:47,880
Come on then!

409
00:21:49,450 --> 00:21:52,050
Merry Christmas!

410
00:22:02,350 --> 00:22:06,050
Well, kids, you really surprised me.

411
00:22:08,850 --> 00:22:09,550
Wow, wow.

412
00:22:10,890 --> 00:22:11,570
What?

413
00:22:12,190 --> 00:22:12,930
Are you counting, kids?

414
00:22:14,950 --> 00:22:16,370
A steam sauna!

415
00:22:16,650 --> 00:22:19,950
This can't be, I've been dreaming of one for years!

416
00:22:25,870 --> 00:22:26,410
Opossum?

417
00:22:28,550 --> 00:22:29,190
Ivuska.

418
00:22:35,250 --> 00:22:43,230
That's weird, it won't keep you warm.

419
00:22:43,750 --> 00:22:45,210
We'll take turns vacuuming.

420
00:22:45,210 --> 00:22:45,810
So what?

421
00:22:46,850 --> 00:22:50,750
Which word on that list looked like MP3 player to you?

422
00:22:51,050 --> 00:22:51,650
None.

423
00:22:52,150 --> 00:22:53,160
But Eva really wanted one.

424
00:22:53,160 --> 00:23:00,590
They're for you too.

425
00:23:00,810 --> 00:23:03,010
Great, carols, a cutter, and measurements.

426
00:23:07,030 --> 00:23:09,490
Marcelka, I'm sorry, I don't have anything for you.

427
00:23:09,530 --> 00:23:12,190
I wanted to buy you something in the January sales.

428
00:23:12,900 --> 00:23:14,020
That's sweet of you, Tomas.

429
00:23:15,050 --> 00:23:15,550
Wow, Barbados!

430
00:23:19,350 --> 00:23:20,510
Wind level two!

431
00:23:25,350 --> 00:23:28,950
Hurricane Dalibor has unexpectedly turned toward Barbados.

432
00:23:29,350 --> 00:23:31,650
Coastal hotels have been devastated.

433
00:23:31,950 --> 00:23:39,750
Participants of the Miss Wet T-Shirt contest were evacuated as a priority, but other guests are completely cut off from the world.

434
00:23:40,350 --> 00:23:41,250
It works!

435
00:23:41,900 --> 00:23:43,260
Thank you, baby Jesus!

436
00:23:43,900 --> 00:23:46,880
And now carols, only a black pre-Christmas one.

437
00:23:46,980 --> 00:23:48,520
No, let's do something traditional.

438
00:23:50,350 --> 00:23:51,500
Gee, Ozzak, I prefer rolls.

439
00:23:51,500 --> 00:23:51,920
Ah!

440
00:23:52,640 --> 00:23:55,900
Farmers, farmers, who gave you a voice?

441
00:23:56,160 --> 00:23:59,880
And trees, balls, rolls, maybe we're going again.

442
00:24:08,750 --> 00:24:11,500
Hello, delivery from Barbados for Mr. Ozzak.

443
00:24:11,500 --> 00:24:12,320
That's for me!

444
00:24:12,900 --> 00:24:13,780
Here it is.

445
00:24:13,940 --> 00:24:14,400
Yeah, I'll take it.

446
00:24:22,450 --> 00:24:23,510
Well, goodbye.

447
00:24:23,510 --> 00:24:24,690
Goodbye.

448
00:24:24,770 --> 00:24:24,990
Gift.

449
00:24:27,250 --> 00:24:28,150
Ivuska, we're going to need a club.

450
00:24:44,750 --> 00:24:47,400
Farmers, farmers, who...

451
00:24:47,400 --> 00:24:48,160
who gave you a voice.

452
00:24:48,320 --> 00:24:52,180
And trees, balls, rolls, we can again.

453
00:24:52,180 --> 00:25:00,150
But it seems, the manger, donkey by the crib, a golden pig in the morning will paint it for you.

454
00:25:01,950 --> 00:25:07,210
It depends on whether it snows, we'll call baby Jesus to bristle up for us.

455
00:25:07,210 --> 00:25:11,250
And rolls, rolls, who gave you a voice?

456
00:25:11,430 --> 00:25:15,270
Was it baby Jesus the great, or Old Man Frost?

457
00:25:15,620 --> 00:25:18,940
Farmers, farmers, what's ringing inside them?

458
00:25:19,550 --> 00:25:24,750
Trees, balls, rolls, guys.
